    <div class = 'subheading'>
    What's the Electronic Vital Sign Montior?
    </div>
    <div class = 'description'>
        <div class= 'ESVM'>
            <div>
            <a href="https://www.webmd.com/cancer/vital-signs-monitor#1">
            <img class= 'monitor-image' src="Vitals.jpg" alt="Electronic Vital Sign Monitor">
            </a>
            </div>
            <div>
                The Electronic Vital Sign Monitor is a machine that generally measures heart rate, blood pressure, oxygen level, body temperature, and respiratory rate. The current monitor deployed in hospitals audibly represents only heart rate and blood pressure. Heart rate is sonified through rhythm and blood pressure through pitch. Heart rate is sonified through rhythm: the audible beep indicates a heartbeat and the silence signifies the gap between each heartbeat. Blood pressure is sonified into audio by pitch: the higher the pitch, the higher the blood pressure. 
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class = 'subheading'>
        What's New?
    </div>
    <div class = 'description'>
        Oxygen level is added to the current audio that includes heart rate and blood pressure audio through timbre. Timbre is the third dimension of sound; it is what differentiates one instrument sound from another.
    </div>
    <div class = 'subheading'>
        How is it Done?
        </div>
    <div class = 'description'>
        Two different sound sources, oscillators (synthesized square and sine sound waves) and musical instruments (cello and French horn), in their ability to represent oxygen content as timbre. The two oscillators are combined by playing both oscillators at the same time at different volumes to create a range of timbres. In contrast, the instruments are combined through interpolating the timbre using a neural network. These two methods of timbre, sonified alongside pitch and rhythm generate the audio signal of the new Electronic Vital Sign Monitor.

    </div>
